---
import Callout from "@luciodale/docs-ui-kit/components/Callout.astro";
import CodeBlock from "@luciodale/docs-ui-kit/components/CodeBlock.astro";
import Comparison from "@luciodale/docs-ui-kit/components/Comparison.astro";
import ContentSection from "@luciodale/docs-ui-kit/components/ContentSection.astro";
import InlineCode from "@luciodale/docs-ui-kit/components/InlineCode.astro";
import DocsPage from "../../layouts/DocsPage.astro";
import { href } from "../../lib/link";

export const prerender = true;
---

<DocsPage
	title="swipe-bar vs Vaul"
	description="How swipe-bar compares to Vaul. Honest trade-offs on side drawers vs bottom sheets, snap points, multi instance support, dependencies, and mobile feel for React."
>
	<ContentSection label="The choice">
		<p class="text-white/60 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
			Vaul (by Emil Kowalski, widely adopted at Vercel) is the modern
			answer for iOS style drawers in React. It's gesture driven, spring
			animated, accessible through Radix Dialog primitives, and polished
			to the point that using it feels closer to a native sheet than
			most web libraries manage. Bottom drawers with numeric snap points
			are its bread and butter.
		</p>
		<p class="text-white/60 leading-relaxed">
			swipe-bar aims at the adjacent problem. It's opinionated toward
			left, right, and bottom sidebars as peers, with multi instance
			support on the same edge, mouse and touch parity on desktop, and
			zero runtime dependencies. The feel is similar. The API and scope
			aren't.
		</p>
	</ContentSection>

	<ContentSection label="Where each one sits">
		<p class="text-white/60 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
			Vaul is a drawer primitive with a strong bottom sheet identity.
			You compose its controlled <InlineCode>&lt;Drawer&gt;</InlineCode>
			elements, pick snap points, and let Radix Dialog take care of
			accessibility.
		</p>
		<p class="text-white/60 leading-relaxed">
			swipe-bar is a sidebar system. Provider plus declarative
			components, same API for left, right, and bottom, and a context
			hook for programmatic control. Multi instance and mouse drag are
			first class concerns.
		</p>
	</ContentSection>

	<ContentSection label="Feature by feature">
		<Comparison
			columns={[
				{
					name: "@luciodale/swipe-bar",
					href: "https://www.npmjs.com/package/@luciodale/swipe-bar",
					tagline: "Sidebar system, zero deps, multi instance",
					highlight: true,
				},
				{
					name: "vaul",
					href: "https://www.npmjs.com/package/vaul",
					tagline: "iOS style drawer built on Radix Dialog",
				},
			]}
			rows={[
				{
					feature: "Edge swipe to open",
					description:
						"Drag from the screen edge to reveal the panel on mobile.",
					values: ["yes", "partial"],
				},
				{
					feature: "Drag to close with velocity commit",
					values: ["yes", "yes"],
				},
				{
					feature: "Spring physics",
					values: ["yes", "yes"],
				},
				{
					feature: "Left and right side drawers",
					description:
						"First class side sidebars, same API as bottom.",
					values: ["yes", { text: "Available but bottom-first" }],
				},
				{
					feature: "Bottom sheet with snap points",
					description:
						"Half-open stop and full-open stop.",
					values: [
						{ text: "mid anchor point" },
						{ text: "numeric snap array, richer API" },
					],
				},
				{
					feature: "Multi instance per side",
					description:
						"Two or more drawers on the same edge, independent state.",
					values: ["yes", "no"],
				},
				{
					feature: "Mouse drag on desktop",
					description:
						"Same gesture on pointer devices, not only touch.",
					values: ["yes", "no"],
				},
				{
					feature: "Nested drawers",
					description:
						"Push another drawer from inside an open one.",
					values: ["no", "yes"],
				},
				{
					feature: "Accessibility",
					description:
						"Focus trap, Escape, aria attributes.",
					values: [
						"yes",
						{ text: "Radix Dialog backed" },
					],
				},
				{
					feature: "Runtime dependencies",
					values: [
						{ text: "Zero" },
						{
							text: "Radix Dialog + primitives",
						},
					],
				},
				{
					feature: "Production track record",
					values: [
						{
							text: "In production at a major bank, hundreds of thousands of users",
						},
						{ text: "Adopted at Vercel, battle tested" },
					],
				},
				{
					feature: "Best fit",
					values: [
						{
							text: "Side drawers, multi instance, PWAs. Themeable to match any native look, iOS included.",
						},
						{ text: "Bottom sheet with snap points, nested drawer flows." },
					],
				},
			]}
			caption="Feature comparison between swipe-bar and Vaul"
		/>
	</ContentSection>

	<ContentSection label="Scope shape, not quality">
		<p class="text-white/60 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
			Both libraries do gesture, physics, and accessibility well. The
			distinction is intent.
		</p>
		<p class="text-white/60 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
			Vaul is optimized for the pattern iOS and Android users recognize
			as a bottom sheet: numeric snap points, nested push flows,
			dynamic content height, Radix a11y guarantees. It shines in
			mobile-first product UX where the bottom sheet is the primary
			surface.
		</p>
		<p class="text-white/60 leading-relaxed">
			swipe-bar is optimized for nav and settings drawers that live on
			the side, with the same gesture grammar also available on the
			bottom edge. Two settings drawers on the right edge, a nav on the
			left, and a bottom sheet is a shape swipe-bar models directly.
		</p>
	</ContentSection>

	<ContentSection label="Multi instance, side by side">
		<p class="text-white/60 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
			swipe-bar treats every sidebar as an independent instance
			identified by an <InlineCode>id</InlineCode>. Opening the nav drawer
			doesn't prevent opening a settings drawer from the same edge. The
			z-index and overlay stacking stay consistent because the provider
			orchestrates it centrally.
		</p>
		<CodeBlock
			code={`<SwipeBarLeft id="nav" isAbsolute>
  <Nav />
</SwipeBarLeft>

<SwipeBarLeft
  id="settings"
  isAbsolute
  swipeToOpen={false}
  swipeBarZIndex={70}
  overlayZIndex={65}
>
  <Settings />
</SwipeBarLeft>`}
			language="tsx"
			filename="multi-instance.tsx"
		/>
		<p class="text-white/60 mt-4 leading-relaxed">
			Vaul treats a drawer as a dialog. Opening two at once on the same
			edge isn't a pattern the library models natively, and you'd end
			up coordinating state yourself.
		</p>
	</ContentSection>

	<ContentSection label="Dependency weight">
		<p class="text-white/60 leading-relaxed">
			Vaul depends on Radix Dialog, which itself pulls a small tree of
			Radix primitives. That's a fair price for the accessibility
			guarantees and the existing Radix ecosystem familiarity. swipe-bar
			keeps the bundle lean and implements the accessibility pieces
			itself. If you already use Radix across your app, Vaul's extra
			weight is free. If you don't, swipe-bar's zero-dep claim is real.
		</p>
	</ContentSection>

	<ContentSection label="When to pick Vaul">
		<Callout type="info" title="Pick it when">
			Your primary surface is a bottom sheet and the snap point grammar
			matters. You want nested drawer flows. You're already on
			Radix / shadcn and want consistent accessibility primitives. You
			value battle testing at Vercel scale over bundle minimalism.
		</Callout>
	</ContentSection>

	<ContentSection label="When to pick swipe-bar">
		<Callout type="tip" title="Pick it when">
			Your UX has navigation, settings, or filter drawers on the sides.
			You need two or more drawers on the same edge. Desktop mouse
			users should get the same drag gesture as mobile touch users. You
			want zero runtime dependencies in the bundle.
		</Callout>
	</ContentSection>

	<ContentSection label="Next steps">
		<ul class="space-y-2 text-white/60">
			<li>
				<a href={href("/docs/vs-shadcn-sheet")} class="text-accent hover:underline">vs shadcn sheet</a> — when you want a modal, not a drawer
			</li>
			<li>
				<a href={href("/docs/getting-started")} class="text-accent hover:underline">Getting started</a> — install and wire up a sidebar
			</li>
			<li>
				<a href={href("/docs/bottom-sheets")} class="text-accent hover:underline">Bottom sheets</a> — mid anchor and full sheet patterns
			</li>
		</ul>
	</ContentSection>
</DocsPage>
